housands of miles following the knots, shivering with the birds out on the snowy tundra, tracking them down in bug-infested marshes, Cramer vividly portrays what’s at stake for millions of shorebirds and hundreds of millions of people living at the sea edge. The Narrow Edge offers an uplifting portrait of the tenacity of tiny birds and of the many people who, on the sea edge we all share, keep knots flying and offer them safe harbor. Winner of the 2016 National Academies Communications Award for best book that honors the best in science communications. Sponsored by the Keck Futures Initiative—a program of the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, with the support of the W.M. Keck Foundation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCalidrisxEcology. 0aClimatic changesxAtlantic OceanxDelaware Bay. 0aClimatic changesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aHuman ecology. 0aLimulus polyphemusxEcology. 0aMigratory birdsxDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 0aMigratory birdszDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 0aRed knotxMigrationxDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 0aRed knotxMigrationzDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 0aSeashore ecologyxAtlantic Coast (America). 0aSeashore ecologyzAtlantic Coast (America). 0aShore birdsxMigrationxDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 0aShore birdsxMigrationzDelaware Bay (Del. and N.J.). 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ornithology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021371340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213713423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213713/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles